article.description:
Ray Allen admitted he was anxious all day because
he knew he was going to be compared to Gary Payton.
article.headline: Allen scores 23 as Seattle keeps Detroit down

images.name: Allen_Ray 030224 Inline
images.caption: Ray Allen connected on seven of 18 shots in his Seattle home debut.

article.linkText: Allen repays Sonics fans for their warm welcome
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Ray Allen admitted he was anxious all day because he knew he was going to be compared to Gary Payton. ''I was very nervous because I wanted to do so well,'' Allen said after scoring 14 of his 23 points in the second half of the Seattle SuperSonics' 86-79 victory over the Detroit Pistons on Monday night. It was Allen's first game in Seattle as a member of the SuperSonics. ''I was just so nervous shooting some of my shots because I wanted to make them so bad,'' the three-time All-Star shooting guard said. ''I think normally when I shoot, I don't worry about it. I just shoot the ball.'' Allen, who also had eight assists, was happy to get a victory to show the fans of Seattle that the SuperSonics made a smart move when trading Payton to Milwaukee in exchange for him. ''I was just so pleased to feel welcome,'' he said. ''Emotionally, coming off the trade, that was one of my biggest worries: Coming in and not being welcomed.'' The Sonics, who lost to the Lakers in Los Angeles in Allen's debut in a Seattle uniform Sunday night, handed the Pistons their third consecutive defeat. Detroit fell into a tie with idle Indiana for first place in the Central Division. The trade of Payton, a nine-time All-Star and a veteran of 12½ seasons with the Sonics, has been an unpopular one, but Allen was cheered loudly after his 7-for-18 shooting night. Seattle coach Nate McMillan said he thinks Seattle's fans, while disappointed to lose a star like Payton, will love Allen's game, too. ''The guy can play,'' McMillan said. ''He's fun to watch. He does a lot of things on the floor. It's hard to read where he will be and what he will do because he can do so many things.'' Rashard Lewis had 22 points and eight rebounds for the Sonics, who sent Payton and Desmond Mason to Milwaukee in exchange for Allen and two other players Thursday. Richard Hamilton scored 22 points and Ben Wallace pulled down 17 rebounds for the Pistons. Hamilton fouled out with 3:14 go with his third foul of the fourth quarter, all against Allen. When Hamilton fouled out, Seattle led 78-73. The Sonics outscored the Pistons 9-6 the rest of the way. Kevin Ollie, a journeyman point guard who came to Seattle from Milwaukee along with Allen, was happy to see Allen have success. ''The big key for Ray is winning,'' Ollie said. ''It's not about numbers for Ray, it's about wins. I think that's the kind of character he has as a person and a player. He wants to win no matter if he gets 20 points or 10 points.'' Detroit led 62-60 after Chucky Atkins' 3-point shot 55 seconds into the fourth quarter, but the Sonics answered that with eight consecutive points, including a 3-pointer and two fastbreak layups by Allen, to take a 71-62 lead. The Pistons led 57-56 after Chauncey Billups' layup with 3:02 left in the third quarter. Hamilton put them up three with a driving 5-footer. But Predrag Drobnjak's 3-point shot on a fastbreak with 1:34 left in the period tied the score at 59. The Sonics led 45-39 at halftime after grabbing a 21-10 lead on a 15-footer by Lewis with 5:31 left in the first quarter. McMillan was whistled for a technical with 2:36 to go in the first half after arguing a foul called on Drobnjak. The Sonics outscored the Pistons 10-5 in the final 5½ minutes of the opening half, with Lewis scoring eight of them and Allen making two free throws with 17.8 seconds to go. The Pistons, who have lost three in a row for the second time this season, will play Tuesday night in Sacramento and Thursday night in Los Angeles against the Lakers. Detroit lost the first game of a five-game West Coast road trip. ''You have to be concerned,'' the Pistons' Cliff Robinson said. ''We wanted to start off the trip with a win, but we didn't. It's just the matter of getting back to playing the way we need to be successful.'' Hamilton said the Pistons are good enough to win the final four games of their road trip, but they're going to be tested. ''We'll find out a lot about ourselves,'' he said. Game notes
Allen's teams are 4-1 against the Pistons this season. In Milwaukee this season, the Bucks were 3-1 against Detroit. ... The Sonics are 13-12 at home, the first time they've been above .500 in the Key Arena since Dec. 7 when they were 5-4. ... Seattle won for just the second time in nine games against the Pistons. ... McMillan has named Brent Barry to replace Payton as the Sonics' captain.
